{"key":"post-10056205","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10056205</id>\n<content>The pillow case method has to be the worst possible pasteurization procedure, and is messy to boot.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Mix all your substrate ingredients except the verm together and bring to field capacity.&amp;nbsp; Next, hydrate the verm to field capacity, and then mix it into the previously hydrated manure/coir/etc.&amp;nbsp; I'd suggest verm at up to 50% by volume of your substrate mix, since cow manure can be quite muddy without the verm.&amp;nbsp; Use gypsum at up to ten percent, but at least 5%.(just eyeball it.&amp;nbsp; One handful of gypsum for each 20 handfuls of substrate mix)&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Load into quart jars and pasteurize in a large pot of water on the stove.&amp;nbsp; You'll probably want to bring the water to a boil for the first ten minutes or so.&amp;nbsp; When your thermometer reads 140F in the center of one of the jars, shut off the stove for a few minutes, since the temp in the jars will continue to rise.&amp;nbsp; Maintain 140F to 160F for one hour by manipulating your stove setting.&amp;nbsp; You'll have to babysit it the first time or two you use this method, but then you'll have the routine down and can just repeat it after that.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10056584</next>\n<prev>10055756</prev>\n<first>10055756</first>\n<last>11247289</last>\n<when>1238203596</when>\n<utime>03/28/09 04:26 AM</utime>\n</post>"}